post_text:
This Wednesday night, our own Franklin High School Principal, Michael Vuolo, will be throwing out one of the first pitches at the Milwaukee Milkmen game as part of our partnership with GPS Education Partners. GPS works to partner Franklin High School students with local businesses so they can explore technical career pathways as a viable career choice.

GPS recognized Mr. Vuolo recently and presented him with a "Milkmen Basket" at school. We thank GPS and the Milwaukee Milkmen for recognizing the hard work our schools are doing right now to keep the environment safe and open for our students and families. #BetterCommunity

A mural is a painting or work of art executed directly on a wall, usually created in public locations for public visibility. 7th Grade Students have been busy learning about and creating murals. These murals are based on what is happening in the world around them. Students also had the opportunity to study different murals and explain why they like them. #FPMSWildcats #BetterPlaceToLearn #prideFPS

May 7 at 5:14 PM ·

During this Staff Appreciation Week (and with Tuesday being "National Teacher Day"), this is a very timely share.

From Student Council: Thank you, FPMS Staff! These days, teaching looks a little bit different and can have its challenges. The students from Forest Park Middle School recognize this, and wanted to say thank you to all the staff members going above and beyond. With the help of their classmates, Student Council Representatives organized and produced this Staff Appreciation Video to express their gratitude to everyone working at FPMS! We thank you, we miss you, and we can't wait to see you all soon!

post_text:
“When I am feeling alone, I like to do activities that make me happy and remind me of my
talents. Some of these activities include drawing, running/working out, listening to music,
cooking, and spending time with my family.” - A teen in WI #YouAreNotAlone #ShareMyStory #childrensmentalhealthmatters

Today is Children's Mental Health Awareness Day. Let's not forget during this time of self-isolation that our children might need more help from us in terms of mental health. You can find more resources here that might help: https://children.wi.gov/pages/home.aspx

We are very pleased and proud to share that Franklin High School has once again been ranked as one of the "Best High Schools" in the nation by U.S. News and World Report. FHS ranked 37th out of 551 high schools in the state of Wisconsin (top 7%) and 1,282nd out of over 24,000 high schools nationally (top 6%).

Schools are ranked on their performance on state-required tests, graduation and how well they prepare students for college. Follow the link below to see more about the report. #BetterPlaceToLearn

post_text:
This week is "School Social Work Week." Our work with Social Emotional Learning (SEL) in the District could not be done without these trained mental health professionals that help to be that link between home and school for our students. They help families where needed and are a vital part of our success. They work to lead trainings with emergency responders in the community and also train up our teachers on how to best work with children that have specific needs. Thank you for the work you do! #BetterCommunity

More info about the work of a School Social Worker here: https://www.sswaa.org/school-social-work

post_text:
Tonight is the night! No passport needed to journey around the world. The FHS Culture Fest will be in the main commons from 5:30 to 7:30. This event is about celebration and unity. Events like these that build a cohesive community deter events like the Sikh Temple shooting in Oak Creek 7 years ago. We will have a special memorial and award-winning documentary produced by FHS graduate Jacob Young. The evening will be started by Pardeep Singh Kaleka, a community peace activist whose father was killed in the shooting. This is our time to come together and make a difference. This free event will also fill your belly with delicious food, feed your mind with cultural adventures and fill your heart with celebration. Bring your family and friends. #BetterCommunity

Here is the event page with more details if needed: https://www.facebook.com/events/2556233201314253

This weekend! Come check out the Forest Park Middle School - Franklin, WI Drama Club production of "Hotel Escargot!" This Friday, March 6 at 7pm in the Forest Park Commons.

Tickets are $3/student & $6/adult. Tickets can be purchased online or at the door. Purchase online tickets here: https://fpmsdrama.brownpapertickets.com

Synopsis: Take a hilarious trip to the Kantz France International Film Festival in the French Riveria with the FPMS Drama Club. A hodgepodge of people come together at the elegant Hotel Escargot — the downtrodden hotel staff, a couple of bumbling jewel thieves, wealthy guests, an inept reporter, and directors, producers, actors, investors and movie fans from all over the world! Don’t miss this fun whodunit…well kind of a whodunit....and support your fellow students and the performing arts! #BetterCommunity

Special thanks to Volition Franklin and the PAWS at Forest Park Middle School for helping to sponsor this event! #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterCommunity

post_text: Recently, more Franklin staff opted to come in on a Saturday to get CPR certified. What made this training extra special was that it was organized by two Franklin High School students - Meredith and Samantha. They were doing a a citizenship project for their American Government class that focused on making an impact on the community. Meredith's dad is a Battalion Chief with the Franklin Fire Department, who is also a certified CPR instructor, so she asked him to donate his time to teach some classes. The girls worked with our nursing staff to advertise the opportunity and to set up space. They drafted newsletter communications for staff and presented at an FHS staff meeting. So far they have held 1 of 2 classes! #BetterCommunity

We continue to be so proud of the staff that helped save Hunter's life in January. Children's Wisconsin just released this story today. They did a great write-up about Hunter's story, middle schooler Maddie's story, the importance of AED's in schools, the work of Project ADAM, the work of the Herma Heart Institute at Children's Wisconsin (a top pediatric heart institution), and the recognition of our nursing and Emergency Response Team staff. This is really worth the read and we thank Children's Wisconsin for their continued work around everything involving the heart. #BetterCommunity

Thank you to our Franklin High School counselors Diane Gilroy, Amy Oost, Keith Decker & Mandy Kluck!

National School Counseling Week (#NSCW2020) is this week Feb. 3–7, 2020. The week, sponsored by the American School Counselor Association (ASCA), highlights the unique contribution of school counselors within U.S. school systems and the tremendous impact they can have in helping students achieve school success and plan for a career. Take a moment to thank your local school counselor(s). Follow #NSCW2020 on social media.

To learn more about National School Counseling Week, visit www.schoolcounselor.org/nscw

Forest Park 7th and 8th Grade "Future Cities" teams competed last week at the Regionals Competition. Congratulations to the following teams that competed at the Milwaukee School of Engineering (MSOE):

The Forest Park teams did very well, taking home the following awards:

“Best Healthcare System”: Team Akiko Sen
“Best Use of Recreational Space”: Team Taronga Waters
“Most Resilient Storm Sewer System” Team Terravale

Out of 52 teams at Regionals (and 190 teams that competed overall in the state of Wisconsin), Forest Park’s 8th grade team, Akiko-Sen, took 5th place overall! Congratulations! #BetterPlaceToLearn

Our Forest Park Middle School Tech Ed Dept hosted "Plastivan" last week which is a group that comes to teach kids more about chemical reactions, recycling and re-using plastics in different ways. Students skewered a balloon without popping it and created some chemical reactions that resulted in plastics. This was made possible by a grant from the Society of Plastics Engineers.

Thanks to Mark Wolverton of SPE: Inspiring Plastics Professionals for sharing your knowledge with our students! #BetterPlaceToLearn

post_text: At Wednesday night's School Board meeting, a Franklin High School student (Sean) was awarded the rank of Eagle Scout and recognized by the School Board. Sean chose a project to help Franklin residents properly retire American flags in a dignified way by constructing three American flag retirement collection boxes. He also coordinated with the Franklin Police Department and Franklin Fire Department to place the boxes at their locations. This project not only honors our American flag, our veterans and all who serve, but also educates our community. Thank you, Sean and Congratulations! #BetterCommunity

post_text: From one of our music educators: "Franklin Energizers Show Choir has their final preview run-through of our competition show tonight (Thursday) at 7pm in the Saber Center. It should be no longer than 30 minutes (our show is about 20 minutes total). We travel to La Crosse tomorrow for the weekend, and our first competition is at Viterbo on Saturday. If you are free, we'd love for you both to attend. Our theme is "Stoicheion: The Root of All Things"....From water, earth, fire and air our show helps breathe energy back into the everyday grind, and ground us as we find our way through life. Hope to see you there!"

post_text:
Yesterday at Forest Park, 7th and 8th Grade students participated in the "Future Cities" competition. Future City Competition is a project-based learning program where students in 6th, 7th, and 8th grades imagine, research, design, and build cities of the future. Volunteer judges were comprised of engineers from CSD Structural Engineers and past Future City students.

Congratulations to the winning teams!
7th grade - 1st place - Terravale
8th grade - 1st place - Akiko-Sen
Runner-ups: Sambatra and Taronga Waters

Thank you to Mrs. Fassbender, Mrs. Gorak and Mrs. Laffin for running this program!

This morning, Forest Park 7th Graders welcomed Mr. Jason Dropik, the Head of School for Indian Community School, our neighbor school in Franklin. Mr. Dropik talked about his native American heritage and what it has been like to grow up as a Native American in the United States.

Students are studying about groups in the United States that have been traditionally marginalized. Students will then explore the tensions that existed for those marginalized groups and decide what public policies need to change for those affected. #BetterPlaceToLearn

post_text: Last night's "Community Conversation" session invited employers, college leaders, community leaders, families, and high school students to gather and discuss opportunities for youth with disabilities in regards to postsecondary education and employment in the workforce. The session was organized by Victoria Jensen, our Transition Coordinator and Life Skills Teacher at the high school. Attendees heard from FHS alumni about their experiences in the workforce. Dr. Laura Owens from Creative Employment Opportunities, Inc. lead the group through some exercises that invited discussion about how to open up opportunities for youth with disabilities. This event was made possible by the Transition Initiative Grant. #BetterCommunity

post_text: Giving is the way of the season. Staff members at our District Office have been taking part in December fundraiser activities to raise money for the The Salvation Army Oak Creek Food and Toy Drive that is taking place this coming Saturday. Staff members could purchase ornaments for the ECC tree and partake in food days for small fees that all accounted for $1,150 funds raised this year! This morning, at a staff breakfast, Dr. Mueller presented Ken Tregallas from Salvation Army with our contribution. Over the past 11 years, the District Office staff has raised over $13,000 for Salvation Army with our December Giving Back Campaign. Thanks to the District Office "Fun Committee" (who are all fully represented in the group picture) for setting up these fundraiser opportunities. #BetterCommunity

Members of the community, including local Franklin Police Department, Franklin Fire Department, and Volition Franklin
members attended a Youth Mental Health First Aid clinic put on by our Franklin Public Schools Student Service staff. Brandi Clauff and Kristin Lorino lead the workshop to educate participants about risk factors and warning signs of mental health problems in adolescents. Topics covered included the importance of early intervention and how to help an adolescent in crisis. This is a great example of local agencies coming together to all create a #BetterCommunity.

Franklin art students raise finds for Hunger Task Force to help local families in need
text:
Thanks to the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel (Franklin NOW) for covering our Feeding Franklin event from this past weekend. Some great photography that captured the little moments. Feeding Franklin took in over $2500 to go towards Hunger Task Force, Inc.! Such a great event. Thanks to the community for turning out and to the students who created the bowls that were sold by the Art Department. #BetterCommunity

Congratulations to the Franklin Varsity Dance Team for all their hard work that is paying off! Great post below and you can also check out the Dad's Dance routine at the link below. "Who you gonna call?" #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterCommunity

Dad's Dance Routine is here: https://youtu.be/ahZFCF--uRY
shared_text:
Franklin Varsity Dance Team
December 8, 2019 at 1:41 PM ·

When you cry twice in one day because you are so so proud then it’s a pretty spectacular day!!! Beyond proud of this crew! FHS debuted their jazz routine and it was SHOW STOPPING! They were also champions of the day on Side A! And Spirit has some solid performances winning highest score of the day in BOTH Pom AND jazz!!!! Our mini and prep teams also had great performances and are getting better and better each time!!!! Hard work pays off and we will keep working! #GBBB #DreamCrazier #Work

post_text:
Don't forget! FEEDING FRANKLIN is coming up this Saturday and is being put on by our Art Department. Join us from 11a-2p at Forest Park Middle School. Students have created over 500 ceramic bowls to sell. Please also bring low-sugar cereal box donations if you are able.

NEW INFORMATION: We just got word that Panera Bread soup is being served! We will have Tomato, Broccoli and Cheddar and Chicken Noodle on hand along with bread. Make a meal at this great event and help to give back locally to the area.

All proceeds go towards Hunger Task Force, Inc..

post_text: Franklin High School students participated in a cultural festival on Monday as part of Mrs. Thoen’s AP Human Geography class. The unit dedicated to culture invited students to share a little about their own culture in the way of food. Students brought food to share a little more about their ancestry. Such a great way to create #BetterCommunity and a #BetterPlaceToLearn

post_text: During American Education Week, we give a special shout out and heartfelt thank you to the volunteers in the buildings! These pictures are from the Ben Franklin Math Club - an 8 week lunch time session of math enrichment for 3rd-5th grade students. It is run by parent volunteers and open to any 3rd-5th grade student who wanted to explore math with their peers. Thank you, volunteers for making this possible! #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterCommunity #AEW2019

post_text: The Ben Franklin 1st Grader WORD DETECTIVES were given a mission on Thursday by an agent of the SSDA (Super Secret Detective Agency). The students all had to work together and piece together clues to unravel the mystery statement. In the end, they did figure out the final statement and were rewarded with light up WORD SEARCHERS (aka "finger lights"). Thank you to Ms. Mix and Mrs. Steeves for helping our Word Detectives to complete their case! #BetterPlaceToLearn

post_text: Our staff developer from the Reading and Writing Project out of Teachers College, Columbia University in New York was on-site at FPMS this Week. Mandy Ehrlich worked with our literacy teachers in grades 6-8 to develop their capacity of reading and writing instruction. The two days of personal growth for our teachers will benefit our middle school students ability to read and write for real reasons. Mandy will be back three more times this year to work with our middle school literacy teachers to improve their practice and outcomes for all FPMS kids! #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterPlaceToWork

post_text: It was a very special day for Ms. Mix's and Mrs. Steeves' Ben Franklin 1st Graders. They have been playing WORD DETECTIVE in class recently and receiving word clues and missions from a member of the SSDA (Super Secret Detective Agency). Today, an agent from the SSDA came in to deliver their final clues and mission in person. Thank you to SSDA Agent Christopher Reuter (who moonlights as our Director of Teaching & Learning) for making this a fun day for the students! Check back tomorrow for some pictures and to see if the students completed their mission! #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterPlaceToWork

post_text: On Monday, Franklin High School Best Buddies stuffed stockings for Soldiers. The students filled 20 stockings with needed items, made 67 cards and donated an additional 6 bags of supplies. All packages will be delivered overseas through a Soldier Stocking Stuffer program sponsored by Max A. Sass and Sons Funeral Homes. Best Buddies is an International organization designed to promote friendship, inclusion and employment for students with disabilities and their peers. Presently Franklin School District has a high school chapter (for 14 years) and a Middle School Chapter (First official year). Students had a wonderful time participating in this significant event. #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterCommunity

post_text: Health class guest lecture series continued today at Franklin High School. Dr. Ken Strzelecki (from Children's Wisconsin) spoke to students about the real dangers of #Vaping. He encouraged them to be educated about what can happen and what he sees in his practice as a pediatrician. Students were also able to ask questions. Our district nurses also had a discussion with him before the presentation about vaping education, the symptoms to look for and the dangers. #SaberPride #PrideFPS #BetterPlaceToLearn #BetterCommunity #VapingEDU #VapingEducation

The Franklin Board of Education met this week with Senator David Craig to discuss factors that impact district accountability on the Wisconsin State Report Card. For more information, please see the Board of Education Resolution (linked below) from the September 11, 2019 Board Meeting, which will be submitted to the Wisconsin Association of School Boards (WASB) Delegate Assembly for consideration later this year. #BetterCommunity
